	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Trade Commissioner Mandelson addresses ACP ministers</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 December 2003
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> On December 1st 2004, within a week of taking up his post, incoming EU Trade Commissioner Peter Mandelson addressed ACP ministers on the subject of EPAs, the Doha Development Round, and key sectoral issues.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> With regard to EPAs he emphasised the priority accorded to support for regional trade integration, and spoke of the need to 'develop regional markets, with a common set of border measures, tariff and non-tariff, as an incentive for that pivotal requirement for successful development: investment'. He argued that 'setting rules for regional development are at the heart of the EPA process, at the heart of the Cotonou mandate and are central to the road maps that we have jointly agreed for the negotiations'. He concluded that 'only when regional integration is well established, should we pursue a second phase where the objective involves reciprocal access for EU goods and services'. This then would provide the basis for the full integration of ACP countries into the world economy.</p><p> He highlighted the importance of tailoring EPAs to national circumstances and gave an assurance that 'you will be able to protect all sensitive sectors, during a lengthy transition period'.</p><p> Commissioner Mandelson acknowledged that for trade openness to be an important means of generating growth 'the right conditions' have to be in place. By these he meant improving the business climate, establishing appropriate domestic economic policies and following principles of good governance, and he also referred to the need to tackle supply-side constraints.</p><p> On the question of fiscal adjustment, 'the evidence suggests that more reasonable levels of duty would in fact increase ACP fiscal revenues' but he nevertheless did commit the EC to assisting 'the necessary reforms of fiscal structures, away from border taxation towards the taxation of consumer goods'.</p><p> On market-access issues Commissioner Mandelson committed the EU to:</p>
<ul>

<li>putting 'real additional market-access opportunities on the negotiating table for those of you that do not at this stage, benefit from the Everything But Arms initiative'; </li>

<li>revising the rules of origin; and </li>

<li>helping 'developing countries meet our own exacting product standards'.</li>

</ul>
<p>
 Many of these points were taken up in an article published in the UK Guardian, where it became clear that in terms of the EU's contribution to poverty eradication through its global trade policy, the major focus was on the impact of creating trading opportunities for China, India and other large developing countries, where poverty levels are high. The policy measures required for poverty eradication through trade in these countries may well be inconsistent with the short-term interests of ACP countries. <br/> </p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/04/505&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">Speech by Commissioner Mandelson (SPEECH/04/505-1/12/2004)</a> </p><p>
<a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/print/0,3858,5075406-103677,00.html" target="_self">Guardian article by Commissioner Mandelson 'This is our 21st century cha...</a> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/weekly/04-12-08/inbrief.htm#1" target="_self">ICTSD report</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The emphasis placed within the EPA negotiations on supporting regional trade integration largely ignores the extent to which the process of EPA negotiations itself is fragmenting existing trade integration initiatives in eastern and southern Africa. The SADC has in effect been cut in two by the negotiations, while given BLNS membership of the Southern African Customs Union and the commitments made under the SADC trade protocol, the EU-South Africa TDCA effectively pre-empts a majority of the decisions related to the timing, sequencing, and extent of market opening to be undertaken as part of the SADC configuration EPA negotiations.</p><p> Further north, the process of EPA negotiations is creating serious problems for the newly established East African Community Customs Union, with Uganda and Kenya negotiating as part of the ESA configuration and Tanzania negotiating as part of the SADC configuration. The question arises: which sets of tariff-reduction commitments made to the EU will be applicable as part of the common customs tariff which surrounds the territories of the East African Community Customs Union?</p><p> The Commissioner's emphasis on proper sequencing of regional integration with opening to the EU and eventual full integration into the global system, whilst welcome, was undermined by his subsequent insistence that 'EPAs must be in place by January 2008'. This implies that there are very real time constraints on the creation of effectively functioning regional integration initiatives. This could pose a problem in Africa where the effective progress in regional integration has been painfully slow and where EPAs themselves are generating pressures which could fracture the market-integration initiatives.</p><p> While Commissioner Mandelson emphasised the importance of creating the 'right conditions' for 'trade opening' to generate growth, there is little evidence that addressing supply-side constraints (i.e. part of 'creating the right conditions') is being accorded sufficient priority as part of the 9th EDF mid-term review. This is a serious matter, for given the delays in approving new financial allocations and then subsequently committing EDF funds, if programmes to address supply-side constraints are not being designed now they are unlikely to be effectively rolled out until 2012-14 at the earliest. (This is assuming a two-and-a-half-year delay in legally making new funds available - taking us to 2010 - and a further two-and-a-half- to four-year delay in actually moving from primary commitments to secondary commitments and actual payments.</p><p> It needs to be recognised that the key to regional development in Africa is the promotion of a process of regional integration which actually creates trade between neighbouring African countries and encourages the development of local production for national and regional markets. It is not simply about fostering common rules to create a single regional market to facilitate large-scale imports and the distribution thereof.</p><p> Commissioner Mandelson's position on the fiscal issues neglects the fact that EPA negotiations are about tariff elimination not tariff reductions, and that the revenue impact of tariff elimination is quite different from the revenue impact of tariff reductions. If tariffs are eliminated no amount of trade expansion will lead to increased government revenue since no duties will be collected on the expanded volume of trade.</p><p> Finally it should be noted that the Commissioner appeared to raise once more the issue of extending EBA type preferences to ACP countries upon their entry into an EPA, an initiative which the member states' Article 133 Committee has so far declined to discuss.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

